Initial Mechanical Design of a Basic Robotic Dog

Prepared by: Abdullah

1. Robot Body Structure

The robot is designed with a lightweight rectangular chassis that supports all the main components, including the battery, controller, and motors. Keeping these components near the center helps maintain proper balance during operation.

2. Leg Configuration

The robot has four identical legs. Each leg is divided into two sections connected by joints, allowing smooth movement. Rubber pads can be added to the feet to increase grip and reduce slipping.

3. Joints and Degrees of Freedom

Each leg includes:

One hip joint for forward and backward motion.
One knee joint for bending the leg.

This results in:

8 joints in total
8 Degrees of Freedom (DOF)
4. Motor Choice

The MG996R servo motor is selected because it offers:

Reliable torque.
Simple control using a microcontroller.
Good performance for lightweight robotic applications.
Affordable cost for educational projects.
5. Estimated Joint Torque

Assume:

Leg mass = 0.5 kg
Leg length = 0.10 m
Gravitational acceleration = 9.81 m/s²

First, calculate the force:

Force = 0.5 × 9.81 = 4.9 N

Then calculate the torque:

Torque = 4.9 × 0.10 = 0.49 N·m

Therefore, the selected servo motor should provide a torque greater than 0.49 N·m.

6. Balance and Center of Gravity

For better stability, heavy components such as the battery are positioned close to the center of the robot. A lower center of gravity reduces the chance of tipping over while walking.

7. Walking Strategy

A Crawl Gait is chosen as the movement pattern. In this gait, only one leg moves at a time while the remaining three legs stay on the ground, providing continuous support and stability.

8. Possible Mechanical Challenges
Reduced stability on uneven terrain.
Servo motors may overheat under continuous load.
High battery consumption during long operation.
Vibrations caused by rapid leg movement.
Wear of joints after extended use.
Conclusion

This design presents the fundamental mechanical concept of a simple quadruped robot. It emphasizes a lightweight structure, stable walking, proper motor selection, and balanced weight distribution. The proposed design serves as a practical starting point for building and improving a robotic dog in future development.
